'''Draga Garašanin''' ({{lang-sr|Драга Гарашанин}} 1921–1997) was a Serbian archaeologist who studied the [[Eneolithic|Copper]] and [[Bronze Age]] of eastern Europe. She became one of the leading prehistorians of [[Yugoslavia]], later Serbia, after [[World War II]] and with her husband produced the first map of archaeological sites in Serbia.

==Early life==
Draga Arandelović was born on 6 April, 1921 in Paris and obtained her education in [[Belgrade]], which was interrupted by World War II. In 1946 she completed her studies on philology and classic archaeology.{{sfn|Projekta Rastko|2009}} She married {{Interlanguage link multi|Milutin Garašanin|sr|3=Милутин Гарашанин (археолог)}}, also an archaeologist and academic{{sfn|Novaković|2011|p=391}} and the couple subsequently had three daughters, Julija, Sofija and Olivera.{{sfn|Lopušina|2012}} Though they studied with [[Miloje Vasić]], the Garašanins did not agree with his theories and decided to further their studies with {{Interlanguage link multi|Josip Korošec|sl}} at the [[University of Ljubljana]] where they entered in 1950.{{sfn|Novaković|2011|p=391}} Arandelović-Garašanin graduated with her doctorate in 1953, presenting her thesis ''Starčevačka kultura''. The work examined the [[Starčevo culture]] and became an important text for the study of this prehistoric ethnic group.{{sfn|Projekta Rastko|2009}} 

==Career==
Arandelović-Garašanin worked as a volunteer of the [[National Museum of Serbia|Museum of Prince Paul]], which would become the National Museum, beginning in 1942, classifying material from several pre-war excavations. She then briefly worked at the [[Museum of the City of Belgrade]] as the [[curator]] before returning to oversee the National Museum in 1950.{{sfn|Projekta Rastko|2009}}{{sfn|Leksikografski zavod Miroslav Krleža|2016}} In 1951, she and her husband published a gazetteer mapping the archaeological sites in Serbia, ''Arheološka nalazišta u Srbiji'', which was the first effort of its kind in the country.{{sfn|Novaković|2011|p=391}} Her publication ''Katalog metala'' (1954) became a staple,{{sfn|Projekta Rastko|2009}}{{sfn|Leksikografski zavod Miroslav Krleža|2016}} which catalogued metals used in [[Iron Age]] jewelry in the region.{{sfn|Projekta Rastko|2009}}

Arandelović-Garašanin led excavations on numerous important prehistoric sites in Serbia, Macedonia and Montenegro, which included Anzabegovo, Bela Crkva, Kriva Reka, Radanja near [[Štip]], [[Supska]] and [[Žarkovo]].{{sfn|Народни музеј у Београду|2015}} She spent two decades studying Dacian [[necropolis|necropoli]] south of the Danube.{{sfn|Dumitraşcu|2007|p=60}} In addition to her fieldwork, Arandelović-Garašanin arranged the collections and identification of the finds at the National Museum, as well as organizing exhibitions featuring the [[Neolithic]] [[history]] of the [[Central Balkans]], including the [[Dacians|Dacian]] and [[Illyrians|Illyrian]] people from the area. Her exhibits on the [[Bronze Age]] in Serbia toured from the National Museum to Denmark, England and Romania.{{sfn|Народни музеј у Београду|2015}} From 1950 through the 1960s, Arandelović-Garašanin and her husband examined new theories on the chronological prehistory of Serbia, based on the methodology of [[Gero von Merhart]] and {{Interlanguage link multi|Vladimir Milojčić|de}}, of the German school of thought,{{sfn|Novaković|2011|p=391}}{{sfn|Muhly|2004}} The couple became the leading prehistorians after World War II in Serbia{{sfn|Novaković|2011|p=391}} with their collaborations on the Starčevo culture and [[Vinča culture]]s becoming foundational works.{{sfn|Novaković|2011|p=396}}

Arandelović-Garašanin retired from the museum in 1979.{{sfn|Projekta Rastko|2009}} She died on 12 October 1997 in Belgrade, [[Federal Republic of Yugoslavia]].{{sfn|Leksikografski zavod Miroslav Krleža|2016}}

