'''El Porvenir''' is the modern name for a ruined [[Maya city|city]] of the [[pre-Columbian]] [[Maya civilization]] located in the [[Petén (department)|Petén]] department of [[Guatemala]]. Ron Canter, in his paper "The Usumacinta River Portages in the Maya Classical Period" argues that El Porvenir was the first point at which the ancient Maya [[Portage|portaged]] to avoid the unnavigable portions of the [[Usumacinta River]].<ref>{{cite web|title=El Porvenir|url=http://www.mesoweb.com/encyc/index.asp?passcall=rightframeexact&rightframeexact=http%3A//www.mesoweb.com/encyc/view.asp%3Frecord%3D5480%26act%3Dviewexact%26view%3Dnormal%26word%3DPorvenir%26wordAND%3DEl%26redir%3Dno|publisher=Mesoweb Encyclopedia|accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref> A fragment of stone found at the site and aptly called the "El Porvenir Fragment" was also discovered that bore the name of [[Ha' K'in Xook]], the sixth ''ajaw'' of [[Piedras Negras (Maya site)|Piedras Negras]], suggesting a connection to the site.<ref name= mesoweb >{{cite web|title=Ha' K'in Xook|url=http://mesoweb.com/encyc/index.asp?passcall=rightframeexact&rightframeexact=http%3A//mesoweb.com/encyc/view.asp%3Fact%3Dviewexact%26view%3Dnormal%26word%3DXook%26wordAND%3DHa+Kin|publisher=Mesoweb Encyclopedia|accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Teufel|first=Stefanie|title=Die Monumentalskulpturen Von Piedras Negras, Petén, Guatemala|url=http://hss.ulb.uni-bonn.de/2004/0343/0343.pdf|publisher=[[University of Bonn]]|accessdate=February 21, 2014|page=215|language=German|date=2004}}</ref>

